id=3305327623449071&amp;pem=178&amp;tmod=1612512547&amp;ref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F&amp;eae=0&amp;fc=1408&amp;brdim=0%2C0%2C0%2C0%2C1366%2C0%2C1366%2C728%2C1366%2C600&amp;vis=1&amp;rsz=%7C%7Cs%7C&amp;abl=NS&amp;fu=128&amp;bc=31&amp;jar=2021-11-15-14&amp;ifi=2&amp;uci=a!2&amp;btvi=1&amp;fsb=1&amp;xpc=UoLQs5qLgn&amp;p=https%3A//ghextractives.com&amp;dtd=40" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" allowtransparency="true" scrolling="no" allowfullscreen="true" data-google-container-id="a!2" data-load-complete="true" data-google-query-id="CJ6gpcvImvQCFYnydwodg7kImw" style="box-sizing: inherit; width: 797px; max-width: 100%; left: 0px; position: absolute; top: 0px; border-width: 0px; border-style: initial; height: 0px;"></iframe></ins></ins></ins></div><p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 26px; margin-left: 0px; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); font-family: Roboto; font-size: 15px;">In that vein, the government entered into a public-private partnership with an Indian company, Rosy Royal Limited, to refine gold in Ghana.</p><p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 26px; margin-left: 0px; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); font-family: Roboto; font-size: 15px;">The agreement states that the Government of Ghana will receive a 20% equity share in the gold refined by the Indian Company locally, while the Indian investor, which built the refinery gets 80%.</p><p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 26px; margin-left: 0px; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); font-family: Roboto; font-size: 15px;">Wisdom Gomashie, a personal assistant to Deputy Minister of Lands and Natural Resources in charge of Mines,&nbsp;George Mireku Duker, told the Ghana News Agency in an interview on Wednesday.</p><div class="google-auto-placed ap_container" style="box-sizing: inherit; color: rgb(68, 68, 68); font-family: Roboto; font-size: 15px; width: 796.656px; height: auto; clear: both; text-align: center;"><ins data-ad-format="auto" c